  "prompt": "How often do a Tesla's batteries need to be replaced?",
  "response": "Tesla batteries are designed to last a long time, typically between 300,000 to 500,000 miles, depending on the model and usage. In terms of years, this can translate to approximately 8 to 15 years of normal use before a battery might need replacement. Many factors can influence battery lifespan, including driving habits, charging practices, and environmental conditions.\n\nTesla provides a warranty for their batteries, which usually covers 8 years or a certain mileage (e.g., 100,000 to 150,000 miles), whichever comes first, depending on the model. After this period, if the battery's capacity falls below a certain threshold (typically around 70-80%), it may be considered for replacement. \n\nWhile individual experiences can vary, many Tesla owners report that even after several years, their batteries retain a significant portion of their original capacity. Regular maintenance and proper charging habits can further extend the life of a Tesla battery.",
